context: Extending <b5_0>the Gregorian calendar<b5_0/> backwards to dates preceding its official introduction produces a proleptic calendar, which should be used with some <a0_0>caution<a0_0/>. For ordinary purposes, the dates of <b6_0>events occurring <a1_0>prior to 15 October 1582<b6_0/><a1_0/> are generally shown as they appeared in the Julian calendar, with <b8_0>the year<b8_0/> starting on <a4_0>1 January<a4_0/>, and no conversion to their Gregorian equivalents. For example, the Battle of Agincourt is universally considered to have been fought on <a2_0><b7_0>25 October 1415<b7_0/><a2_0/> which is <a3_0>Saint Crispin's Day<a3_0/>.
